explanation:
OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl: need the function prototype/signature to see whether the abs_wakeup_time parameter is declared const (or non-const) in the implementation. A mismatch would affect whether the pointer in the target function could/should be const.

OS_ObjectIdGetById: need its prototype to determine the exact type and const-qualification of the token parameter (and any other pointer parameters). This verifies whether &token is passed to a non-const pointer and whether that influences const-qualification requirements in the caller.

OS_CHECK_POINTER: need the macro/function definition to confirm whether it modifies the pointer argument (e.g. assigns through it) or only inspects it. If the macro writes via the parameter, the pointer cannot be const; if it merely reads/tests for NULL, const is acceptable.

OS_time_t: need the type definition for the pointed-to object to check whether any fields require non-const access or whether the pointed-to type is itself an array/opaque type that would change const-qualification reasoning.

OS_object_token_t: need the typedef/definition to know whether the token is an object that must be modified by callees (i.e. passed as non-const) which affects whether passing &token to helpers requires non-const.

osal_id_t: need the typedef for var_id to confirm it is not a pointer type (and thus irrelevant to pointer constness) and to be thorough about all parameter types used in the function.
